<!DOCTYPE html>
<html><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" version="2.0"><channel><title>Electronics - Ramith's Blog</title><description>Thoughts, stories and ideas.</description><link>https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/</link><image><url>https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/favicon.png</url><title>Electronics - Ramith's Blog</title><link>https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/</link></image><generator>Ghost 2.25</generator><lastBuildDate>Wed, 21 Aug 2019 15:15:28 GMT</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/tag/electronics/rss/" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><ttl>60</ttl><item><title>Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)</title><description>&lt;p&gt;[this post will be updated further with code]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;When I first started out developing our robot for the EN2532 module, I dreamt of having a control panel on a computer which can see what was going on in the robot.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That's when I remembered &lt;a href="https://processing.org/"&gt;processing&lt;/a&gt;, I used back with&lt;a href="https://medium.com/@ramith/motion-sensing-with-intel-edison-41e3cbd4ac5f"&gt; leapmotion&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/making-a-robot-visualisation-platform-from-scratch/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">5d2a9b142a8e8569a1fb43d3</guid><category>Electronics</category><dc:creator>Ramith Hettiarachchi</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 14 Jul 2019 03:26:21 GMT</pubDate><media:content url="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/cover-robot.jpg" medium="image"/><content:encoded>&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/cover-robot.jpg" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;p&gt;[this post will be updated further with code]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;When I first started out developing our robot for the EN2532 module, I dreamt of having a control panel on a computer which can see what was going on in the robot.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That's when I remembered &lt;a href="https://processing.org/"&gt;processing&lt;/a&gt;, I used back with&lt;a href="https://medium.com/@ramith/motion-sensing-with-intel-edison-41e3cbd4ac5f"&gt; leapmotion &amp;amp; Arduino&lt;/a&gt;. So I started out my journey with processing. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Processing&lt;/strong&gt; is a flexible software sketchbook and a language for learning how to code within the context of the visual arts. &lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;I thought of using the HC-05 module to send the data at 230400 baud rate to the computer. Processing's serial library can read the HC-05's input and visualise the coming in.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;You can see the baby stages of the visualiser down below. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;It gets gyro &amp;amp; ToF sensor readings.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-embed-card"&gt;&lt;iframe width="459" height="344" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/XB7BXPco7E0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/PHOTO-2019-05-15-02-04-07.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;(using processing)&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-embed-card"&gt;&lt;iframe width="459" height="344" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HF8FH55gCog?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then I thought of moving to the web because of simplicity. That's when the &lt;a href="https://p5js.org/"&gt;javascript alternative&lt;/a&gt; of processing comes in. I used &lt;a href="https://p5js.org/"&gt;P5.js&lt;/a&gt; along with the serial port library to get my data. Then using relevant mathematical formula I could visualise text, lines, rotation on the canvas&lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/PHOTO-2019-05-24-22-05-40.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;(and added even more features)&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-embed-card"&gt;&lt;iframe width="459" height="344" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/8dNcoAnx7e0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;(in action)&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;p&gt;The final outcome of countless hours spent on javascript. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-width-wide"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/Screenshot-2019-07-14-at-8.54.02-AM.png" class="kg-image" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/Screenshot-2019-07-14-at-8.55.59-AM.png" class="kg-image" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-gallery-card kg-width-wide"&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-container"&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-row"&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-image"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/PHOTO-2019-05-09-16-12-22-2.jpg" width="768" height="1024" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-image"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/PHOTO-2019-05-09-16-12-22-3.jpg" width="768" height="1024" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-image"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/DA2A3CB8-1A19-45F2-BA38-A578CDC29105.JPG" width="3024" height="4032" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-row"&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-image"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/57824158146__D58FD044-6637-4B2B-9F01-F8FF286D433B.jpeg" width="4032" height="3024" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="kg-gallery-image"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/content/images/2019/07/57798446922__DECB91CE-326C-4A2D-8B4E-FA7AA113303B.JPG" width="4032" height="3024" alt="Making a robot Visualisation Platform from Scratch (and how you can do the same)"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;(This board was a custom designed PCB by our Team!)&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title>Voltage Tripler Animation</title><description>&lt;p&gt;Circuit simulation using this amazing app &lt;a href="http://everycircuit.com/"&gt;EveryCircuit&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure class="kg-card kg-embed-card"&gt;&lt;iframe width="459" height="344" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/IQC6u1tV30Y?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</description><link>https://blog.ramith.fyi/static/voltage-tripler-animation/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">5c0ea731aed47507db8b179b</guid><category>Electronics</category><dc:creator>Ramith Hettiarachchi</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 08 Nov 2018 17:50:00 GMT